'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/iamgusain/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### What
Fixing a potential deadlock issue in executor service for interactive request, by shutting down and recreating it.
This issue is reported in this ICM https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/details/264456886/home

### Why
The interactive request executor service can get into a state where an interactive request gets started in CommandDispatcher, but the actual AuthorizationActivity never starts. This can happen when user immediately press home button after starting an acquireToken (interactive) call to push the app in the background. Android 10 (API level 29) and higher place [restrictions ](https://developer.android.com/guide/components/activities/background-starts) on when apps can start activities when the app is running in the background. Because of this the AuthorizationActivity does not start and the request keep waiting for the Authorization Result. Even after broadcasting a "CANCEL_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST" it doesnt finish the request as there are no listener for it.
This blocks any future interactive requests going through the broker as none of them can be assigned the thread. and the user sees an infinite spinner https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/details/264456886/home

### How
When we detect that there is no listener for "CANCEL_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST" (which means that `AuthorizationActivity`/`AuthorizationFragment` hasn't started) but a previous request is still waiting for "RETURN_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST_RESULT" (which means that an interactive request was started in the past), We identify the interactive thread getting stuck (deadlock). Once we run into this situation inorder to process incoming interactive requests, we shutdown the executor service and recreate it since it only has a single thread. This terminates the older thread and starts processing the interactive requests in new thread.

### Testing
**Repro** 
1. Launch MsalTestApp
2. Press AcquireToken
3. Quickly press home button
4. Go back to MsalTestApp to see if it gets stuck in infinite spinner case, if not try from step 2.
5. Press back button to cancel the request, 
6. Try acquireToken again
**Expected**: User should see the credentials page to perform interactive sign-in
**Actual**: User sees the spinner spinning. If you debug in CommandDispatcher.java, you can see that these requests are getting queued but there is already an active request which is still getting processed and doesnt finish.
**AfterFix**: The fix terminates the previous request and continues to process the new request and user sees the credential page to perform sign-in.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/iamgusain/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### What
Fixing a potential deadlock issue in executor service for interactive request, by shutting down and recreating it.
This issue is reported in this ICM https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/details/264456886/home

### Why
The interactive request executor service can get into a state where an interactive request gets started in CommandDispatcher, but the actual AuthorizationActivity never starts. This can happen when user immediately press home button after starting an acquireToken (interactive) call to push the app in the background. Android 10 (API level 29) and higher place [restrictions ](https://developer.android.com/guide/components/activities/background-starts) on when apps can start activities when the app is running in the background. Because of this the AuthorizationActivity does not start and the request keep waiting for the Authorization Result. Even after broadcasting a "CANCEL_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST" it doesnt finish the request as there are no listener for it.
This blocks any future interactive requests going through the broker as none of them can be assigned the thread. and the user sees an infinite spinner https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/details/264456886/home

### How
When we detect that there is no listener for "CANCEL_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST" (which means that `AuthorizationActivity`/`AuthorizationFragment` hasn't started) but a previous request is still waiting for "RETURN_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST_RESULT" (which means that an interactive request was started in the past), We identify the interactive thread getting stuck (deadlock). Once we run into this situation inorder to process incoming interactive requests, we shutdown the executor service and recreate it since it only has a single thread. This terminates the older thread and starts processing the interactive requests in new thread.

### Testing
**Repro** 
1. Launch MsalTestApp
2. Press AcquireToken
3. Quickly press home button
4. Go back to MsalTestApp to see if it gets stuck in infinite spinner case, if not try from step 2.
5. Press back button to cancel the request, 
6. Try acquireToken again
**Expected**: User should see the credentials page to perform interactive sign-in
**Actual**: User sees the spinner spinning. If you debug in CommandDispatcher.java, you can see that these requests are getting queued but there is already an active request which is still getting processed and doesnt finish.
**AfterFix**: The fix terminates the previous request and continues to process the new request and user sees the credential page to perform sign-in.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/iamgusain/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### What
Fixing a potential deadlock issue in executor service for interactive request, by shutting down and recreating it.
This issue is reported in this ICM https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/details/264456886/home

### Why
The interactive request executor service can get into a state where an interactive request gets started in CommandDispatcher, but the actual AuthorizationActivity never starts. This can happen when user immediately press home button after starting an acquireToken (interactive) call to push the app in the background. Android 10 (API level 29) and higher place [restrictions ](https://developer.android.com/guide/components/activities/background-starts) on when apps can start activities when the app is running in the background. Because of this the AuthorizationActivity does not start and the request keep waiting for the Authorization Result. Even after broadcasting a "CANCEL_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST" it doesnt finish the request as there are no listener for it.
This blocks any future interactive requests going through the broker as none of them can be assigned the thread. and the user sees an infinite spinner https://portal.microsofticm.com/imp/v3/incidents/details/264456886/home

### How
When we detect that there is no listener for "CANCEL_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST" (which means that `AuthorizationActivity`/`AuthorizationFragment` hasn't started) but a previous request is still waiting for "RETURN_AUTHORIZATION_REQUEST_RESULT" (which means that an interactive request was started in the past), We identify the interactive thread getting stuck (deadlock). Once we run into this situation inorder to process incoming interactive requests, we shutdown the executor service and recreate it since it only has a single thread. This terminates the older thread and starts processing the interactive requests in new thread.

### Testing
**Repro** 
1. Launch MsalTestApp
2. Press AcquireToken
3. Quickly press home button
4. Go back to MsalTestApp to see if it gets stuck in infinite spinner case, if not try from step 2.
5. Press back button to cancel the request, 
6. Try acquireToken again
**Expected**: User should see the credentials page to perform interactive sign-in
**Actual**: User sees the spinner spinning. If you debug in CommandDispatcher.java, you can see that these requests are getting queued but there is already an active request which is still getting processed and doesnt finish.
**AfterFix**: The fix terminates the previous request and continues to process the new request and user sees the credential page to perform sign-in.

When we are finished with the authorization fragment we attempt to remove ourselves from the provided FragmentManager.  Telemetry provided by some of our consumers shows that in some cases an IllegalStateException is thrown on the call to the FragmentManager to "commit()" the removal of our authorization fragment.  

Adding a link to Android document on [Fragment transactions](https://developer.android.com/guide/fragments/transactions)

Android documentation indicates that commit() should work in the "vast majority" of cases; however in this case it appears to fail as indicated above for some clients.  As a result, this PR adopts the usage of the "commitNow()" method and in addition wraps the calling code in an exception handler in order to be able to log any exception and swallow it.  We're swallowing the exception since this is a clean up step and should not negatively impact the provided activity / fragment manager if it's already been disposed of. +    /**
+     * BouncyCastle doesn't play well with Conscrypt (Android 11's default SSLSocket implementation)
+     * https://developer.android.com/about/versions/11/behavior-changes-all#ssl-sockets-conscrypt
+     *
+     * This causes the DRS request TLS handshake to fail - 'key not found' - even if cert is provided.
+     *
+     * As a short-term work around, we're going to use the 'default' KeyManagerFactory in Android,
+     * and keeps using BouncyCastle in Linux.
+     *
+     * Long term, we're going to move away from platform's default implementation
+     * and use external libraries that are FIPS compliant.
+     *

When we are finished with the authorization fragment we attempt to remove ourselves from the provided FragmentManager.  Telemetry provided by some of our consumers shows that in some cases an IllegalStateException is thrown on the call to the FragmentManager to "commit()" the removal of our authorization fragment.  

Adding a link to Android document on [Fragment transactions](https://developer.android.com/guide/fragments/transactions)

Android documentation indicates that commit() should work in the "vast majority" of cases; however in this case it appears to fail as indicated above for some clients.  As a result, this PR adopts the usage of the "commitNow()" method and in addition wraps the calling code in an exception handler in order to be able to log any exception and swallow it.  We're swallowing the exception since this is a clean up step and should not negatively impact the provided activity / fragment manager if it's already been disposed of. ## The problem 
Addressing bug: https://identitydivision.visualstudio.com/Engineering/_workitems/edit/1776683 
On an Android device without broker, if the first user account is authenticated with CBA, attempting to authenticate subsequent user accounts with CBA fails. Additionally, if a user account ever backs out of the cert picker (the "deny" button), subsequent CBA attempts will result in an error. 
## Why?
There are three main [`ClientCertRequest`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/webkit/ClientCertRequest) methods that can be called on the client side when the user makes a choice on the cert picker: [`proceed`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/webkit/ClientCertRequest#proceed(java.security.PrivateKey,%20java.security.cert.X509Certificate[])), [`cancel`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/webkit/ClientCertRequest#cancel()), and [`ignore`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/webkit/ClientCertRequest#ignore()). We currently only use `proceed` and `cancel`. For `proceed` and `cancel`, Chromium caches the client's choice for the remainder of the app's session. This results in the last choice (whether that's proceeding with a particular cert or choosing to cancel the flow) will be automatically selected whenever the user attempts CBA afterwards. 
## What I did 
The static WebView method [`clearClientCertPreferences`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/webkit/WebView#clearClientCertPreferences(java.lang.Runnable)) clears the cached selection made with [`ClientCertRequest`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/webkit/ClientCertRequest). 
It took some trial and error to find the right place for the method call.  
- Calling `clearClientCertPreferences` right after a `proceed` or `cancel` call (which are both running asynchronously) resulted in either the cache being cleared too early or an error where the cert picker would always appear a second time after authentication. 
- Calling the method at the end of `onReceivedClientCertRequest` resulted in the cache being cleared too early.
- Calling the method in `onChallengeResponseReceived` results in the cert picker appearing twice (similar to first bullet point)

It seemed that I needed to call the method as late as possible in order to ensure that `proceed`/`cancel` would finish first.
The most successful option thus far is clearing the cert preferences cache whenever the WebView reloads a url with a prefix of "https://certauth". The method is called in `onPageLoaded` callback in `onCreateView` in the fragment `WebViewAuthorizationFragment`. 
However, calling `clearClientCertPreferences` introduced a new problem: whenever `cancel` was called, the cert picker would pop up rapidly no less than three times (with the last time being cached). I found that replacing `cancel` with `ignore` seemed to mostly fix the issue. According to [Chromium Code Search](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:android_webview/java/src/org/chromium/android_webview/AwContentsClientBridge.java;drc=48a3eaf6f8ae83f7c99851f0b9088365e3edf6e6;l=120?q=clientcertrequest%20ignore&ss=chromium), the only difference between the two methods on the client side is that `cancel` is cached in a lookup table. 
### Important Note
I have noticed that sometimes, the cert picker will exhibit weird behavior (popping up three times) even with `ignore`. This happened for a period of time while I was testing one day. On that same day (but an hour later) the cert picker was working normally again. I do suspect that this might be some concurrency issue on the client side, but I'm not totally sure. 
Therefore, if you have suggestions on how to improve this fix, *please* let me know!

## How I tested
In AzureSample:
1. Go to Multiple Account Mode
2. Select "Get Graph Data Interactively"
3. Use "vimala@vimrang1.onmicrosoft.com" as upn
4. Select "Sign in with a certificate"
5. From cert picker, select cert with CN=vimala
6. Graph data should show. Click "Get Graph Data Interactively" again
7. Use "mel@vimrang1.onmicrosoft.com" as upn
8. Select "Sign in with a certificate"
9. From cert picker, select "Deny"
10. Should get an "Invalid Request" error. Click back button
11. Use "mel@..." as upn again and select "Sign in with a certificate"
12. From cert picker, select cert with CN=mel
13. Graph data for mel should show

Any time "Sign in with a certificate" is selected, a cert picker should show.

https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-android/pull/1597

## Why?
1. We're not sending x-ms-PKeyAuth to both auth and token endpoint. 
       - we're only sending it to ADAL's token endpoint (which has a totally separate PKeyAuth stack).
3. For some reason, the auth endpoint sends us back PKeyAuth (tested in Broker).
4. The token endpoint is totally busted.

## What I did
1. Make sure we send x-ms-PKeyAuth in both interactive and silent flow.
3. Make sure we're handling the content properly[ based on the spec](https://microsoft.sharepoint.com/:w:/t/aad/devex/EfksUgoBpPNGnACpeQ-_puwBj5JZ616HHxQYxvKJm3JTMg?e=USnvFj).
4. Add tests

## How I tested
1. Install broker
2. Install MSAL test app, signs in interactively* with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com 
3. verify the token with jwt.ms, it should NOT have any deviceid claim in it.
4. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
5. You should get the following error back...

MsalUiRequiredException.
AADSTS50187: Failed to perform device authentication.
Trace ID: ed0290e9-2175-4f5c-85a5-1551076a8900
Correlation ID: b7bad247-913d-499d-b5de-3e94dd474484
Timestamp: 2022-03-03 23:58:12Z

6. signs in interactively with idlab1@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
7. User is prompted for a WPJ registration
8. Click "Register"
9. Get a token back, the token should have deviceid claim in it.
10. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
11. You should get a token back, now the device id claim should be in it.


* by signing in interactively, I mean do not enter login_hint, and select "Use another account" if prompted.
-----

I also added build param to disable silent flow timeout during debugging.
 
This is set to false by default. You can add -PdisableAcquireTokenSilentTimeout in your dev environment command line to turn this on. (In Android studio, go to Preferences -> Complier -> command-line Options and add this param)', 'created_at': '2022-03-03T23:48:46Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-04T00:02:00Z', 'closed_at': None, ## Why?
1. We're not sending x-ms-PKeyAuth to both auth and token endpoint. 
       - we're only sending it to ADAL's token endpoint (which has a totally separate PKeyAuth stack).
3. For some reason, the auth endpoint sends us back PKeyAuth (tested in Broker).
4. The token endpoint is totally busted.

## What I did
1. Make sure we send x-ms-PKeyAuth in both interactive and silent flow.
3. Make sure we're handling the content properly[ based on the spec](https://microsoft.sharepoint.com/:w:/t/aad/devex/EfksUgoBpPNGnACpeQ-_puwBj5JZ616HHxQYxvKJm3JTMg?e=USnvFj).
4. Add tests

## How I tested
1. Install broker
2. Install MSAL test app, signs in interactively* with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com 
3. verify the token with jwt.ms, it should NOT have any deviceid claim in it.
4. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
5. You should get the following error back...

MsalUiRequiredException.
AADSTS50187: Failed to perform device authentication.
Trace ID: ed0290e9-2175-4f5c-85a5-1551076a8900
Correlation ID: b7bad247-913d-499d-b5de-3e94dd474484
Timestamp: 2022-03-03 23:58:12Z

6. signs in interactively with idlab1@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
7. User is prompted for a WPJ registration
8. Click "Register"
9. Get a token back, the token should have deviceid claim in it.
10. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
11. You should get a token back, now the device id claim should be in it.


* by signing in interactively, I mean do not enter login_hint, and select "Use another account" if prompted.
-----

I also added build param to disable silent flow timeout during debugging.
 
This is set to false by default. You can add -PdisableAcquireTokenSilentTimeout in your dev environment command line to turn this on. (In Android studio, go to Preferences -> Complier -> command-line Options and add this param)', 'created_at': '2022-03-03T23:48:46Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-04T00:02:00Z', 'closed_at': None, ## Why?
1. We're not sending x-ms-PKeyAuth to both auth and token endpoint. 
       - we're only sending it to ADAL's token endpoint (which has a totally separate PKeyAuth stack).
3. For some reason, the auth endpoint sends us back PKeyAuth (tested in Broker).
4. The token endpoint is totally busted.

## What I did
1. Make sure we send x-ms-PKeyAuth in both interactive and silent flow.
3. Make sure we're handling the content properly[ based on the spec](https://microsoft.sharepoint.com/:w:/t/aad/devex/EfksUgoBpPNGnACpeQ-_puwBj5JZ616HHxQYxvKJm3JTMg?e=USnvFj).
4. Add tests

## How I tested
1. Install broker
2. Install MSAL test app, signs in interactively* with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com 
3. verify the token with jwt.ms, it should NOT have any deviceid claim in it.
4. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
5. You should get the following error back...

MsalUiRequiredException.
AADSTS50187: Failed to perform device authentication.
Trace ID: ed0290e9-2175-4f5c-85a5-1551076a8900
Correlation ID: b7bad247-913d-499d-b5de-3e94dd474484
Timestamp: 2022-03-03 23:58:12Z

6. signs in interactively with idlab1@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
7. User is prompted for a WPJ registration
8. Click "Register"
9. Get a token back, the token should have deviceid claim in it.
10. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
11. You should get a token back, now the device id claim should be in it.


* by signing in interactively, I mean do not enter login_hint, and select "Use another account" if prompted.
-----

I also added build param to disable silent flow timeout during debugging.
 
This is set to false by default. You can add -PdisableAcquireTokenSilentTimeout in your dev environment command line to turn this on. https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-android/pull/1597

## Why?
1. We're not sending x-ms-PKeyAuth to both auth and token endpoint. 
       - we're only sending it to ADAL's token endpoint (which has a totally separate PKeyAuth stack).
3. For some reason, the auth endpoint sends us back PKeyAuth (tested in Broker).
4. The token endpoint is totally busted.

## What I did
1. Make sure we send x-ms-PKeyAuth in both interactive and silent flow.
3. Make sure we're handling the content properly[ based on the spec](https://microsoft.sharepoint.com/:w:/t/aad/devex/EfksUgoBpPNGnACpeQ-_puwBj5JZ616HHxQYxvKJm3JTMg?e=USnvFj).
4. Add tests

## How I tested
1. Install broker
2. Install MSAL test app, signs in interactively* with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com 
3. verify the token with jwt.ms, it should NOT have any deviceid claim in it.
4. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
5. You should get the following error back...

MsalUiRequiredException.
AADSTS50187: Failed to perform device authentication.
Trace ID: ed0290e9-2175-4f5c-85a5-1551076a8900
Correlation ID: b7bad247-913d-499d-b5de-3e94dd474484
Timestamp: 2022-03-03 23:58:12Z

6. signs in interactively with idlab1@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
7. User is prompted for a WPJ registration
8. Click "Register"
9. Get a token back, the token should have deviceid claim in it.
10. Perform silent request with idlab@msidlab4.onmicrosoft.com **_with device id claim_**
11. You should get a token back, now the device id claim should be in it.


* by signing in interactively, I mean do not enter login_hint, and select "Use another account" if prompted.
-----

I also added build param to disable silent flow timeout during debugging.
 
This is set to false by default. You can add -PdisableAcquireTokenSilentTimeout in your dev environment command line to turn this on.
